<br>
I recently discovered that safer to have critters snared then rooted.<br>
Reason for this is that even snared far reaching mobs like giants or wurms tend to hit me before I can end the casting (and as a result often interrupt me).<br>
Having them rooted gives me the little extra time (even if it breaks) needed to complete the cast and hit for 600 (I'm a wizard) while the snare gives me the extra speed advantage to flee if things go wrong or immobilize it if it flees.<br>
<br>
Don't think this is a solo tactic.. we first came up with this in a group that was lacking melees (only druids, a ranger, a bard and myself) and it proved very effective.<br>
<br>
Deneteth<br>
44 wizard, servant of Mithaniel Maar <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ublakkon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>blakkon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 307<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/1/02 9:47:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=570.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Its about agro...</span><hr size=1> Three reasons, <br>
<br>
1) Snared or not your cleric, wizard, shaman, whatever may want to sit down sooner, and be able to get more mana back while the fight progresses.  A snared mob will still be able to run them down if they have agro from healing you, slowing the monster, or nuking it - if they try and sit, they may get double hit for max damage and interru0pt the fight while the melees chase it around.  Root buy's time for the taunters and melees to get agro,<br>
<br>
2) Agro control.  With root on, whomever is closest to the mob will get agro.  This lets a monk or shaman  (no taunt key) main tank while a rogue backstabs, for example.  It lets melee's distribute the damage more evenly amongst themselves in tougher fights, by just stepping closer or further away.<br>
<br>
3)  Some mobs run early, and others have faster movement rates.  This can cause minor trains or make the group chase it out of the room, even snared there is a chance for training in some dungeons (think Maid/Butler camp in mistmoore- you really don't want the mob to leave the room at all, else you may agro the kitchen staff).<br>
<br>
So its mostly agro control of one form or another.  Now snare is a very nice spell indeed, but given the choice of Snare or root, I will always take both <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . <p>Lorec <br>
Wandering Judge of the Tribunal <br>

Tradesman, Polyglot and Drunken Alchemist</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uuininstormsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Uinin Stormsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/1/02 9:51:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=570.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Its about agro...</span><hr size=1> Throw Selo's Consonant Chain on the pile as well.  When you've got a bard in the group, and the MOB gets all glowy and &quot;is surrounded by chains of music,&quot; it's snared.<br>
<br>
Whether you want to root or not for aggro control is up to you.  Just so you know... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ublakkon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>blakkon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 309<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/1/02 9:56:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=570.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Its about agro...</span><hr size=1> Hehe, aye the bard snare is nice, but the only time I have ever evacced from Maid/Butler (past life) was when the bard missed a note... The mob was halfway out of the castle before we caught it and the resulting train was a sight to behold. <p>Lorec <br>
Wandering Judge of the Tribunal <br>

Tradesman, Polyglot and Drunken Alchemist</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uchinesevboy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Chinese V boy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/1/02 10:03:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=570.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Its about agro...</span><hr size=1> I'd like to point out from experience that there are a LOT of druids/wizzies/rangers/sks who do NOT snare. I've grouped with many nuke/melee druids, while they should be healing/snaring/medding - this has caused a few deaths because of runners and many trains to zone <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So, whenever I'm grouped with above stated classes, I make sure to point out what I expect from them in this group. If they agree and after about 30 mins of mobs running away...then I start casting root. I know the tank will get beat on a bit more, and that root still may break at the worst possible moment...but it's better than nothing.<br>
<br>
-Chosun-<br>
<br>
Give me a good druid any day, great class...but there ARE a high number of idiots who play that class, just seems that there are more bad players playing druids, than there are good players playing druids <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So if you happen to be a GOOD (not alignment, just skill), and happen to be also of the lower 30'ish seasons, please - feel free to send me a tell and we can group. Hard to find good players and YES, I am recruiting hahhahaha <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uwessleythewolf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wessley The Wolf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Wolf</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/1/02 10:43:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=570.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Its about agro...</span><hr size=1> I remember when root overwrote snare.  Though I wasn't a druid back then.  As a rogue using a pair of snare weapons, they finally proc and I say 'SNARED!' and then someone in the group roots because we don't have a specific snarer...  then root wears and of course, it's not snared any more.  /glare/ <p><html>
